        <div class="verdict">✓ Updated April 2026</div>

        <p>Whether you're dispatching plumbers to emergency service calls or managing multi-week installation projects as a commercial subcontractor, your software needs are shaped by the type of work you do. This guide covers the best tools for each plumbing business model.</p>

        <h2>Plumbing service businesses (repair and maintenance)</h2>
        <p>For plumbing companies primarily dispatching technicians to service calls — drain clogs, water heater replacements, fixture installation, leak repair — the software priorities are scheduling efficiency, fast quoting, and invoicing. You need to get technicians to the right address at the right time, give them the tools to quote and invoice on-site, and collect payment before they leave.</p>

        <p><strong>Jobber ($69/mo)</strong> is the go-to for small plumbing service businesses. Quote requests, scheduling, mobile job management, and online payment collection are all handled cleanly. Most small plumbing companies can be fully operational within a day.</p>

        <p>When a plumbing service business grows to 5+ technicians and needs more operational depth — flat-rate pricing, maintenance membership management, and marketing analytics — <strong>ServiceTitan</strong> is the standard upgrade path, despite its higher price and implementation complexity.</p>

        <h2>Commercial plumbing subcontractors</h2>
        <p>Commercial plumbing subcontractors — doing new construction rough-in and trim, commercial tenant improvements, or industrial plumbing under a GC — need project-based management tools, not service dispatch software. The key needs are AIA billing, contract management, job costing against bid, and change order tracking.</p>

        <p><strong>Knowify (~$149/mo)</strong> is purpose-built for commercial subcontractors doing exactly this type of work. AIA G702/G703 pay applications, job cost tracking against contract value, and change order management are the core features. It's the best-fit platform for a commercial plumbing sub in the $1M–$15M revenue range.</p>

        <h2>Residential installation plumbing</h2>
        <p>Plumbing contractors who primarily do new residential construction — rough-in for homebuilders, full bathroom remodels, kitchen reconfigurations — often need project management tools that handle multi-week timelines and GC coordination, without the complexity of full commercial PM platforms.</p>

        <p><strong>Contractor Foreman ($49/mo)</strong> or <strong>Buildertrend ($499/mo)</strong> serve this segment well, depending on scale. Contractor Foreman works for small operations that want more tools at a lower cost. Buildertrend is appropriate for plumbing contractors doing larger residential projects or working closely with homebuilder clients who expect professional project management.</p>

